# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abbeville-south-carolina
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] In 1853 the country contains 89 telegraph lines that stretched 23,261 miles (37,435 km).
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] When published in 1854, the country had an estimated 30,000 miles (48,000 km) of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The **1880 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office during June 1880, was the tenth United States census.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] It was the first time that women were permitted to be enumerators.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The Superintendent of the Census was Francis Amasa Walker.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York City—recorded a population of over one million, and the first census in which the 20 most populated cities all recorded over 100,000 residents.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] Schedule 4 (Social statistics) was the responsibility of experts and special agents, rather than the enumerators.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The majority of the data came from correspondence with officials of institutions providing care and treatment of certain members of the population.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] Experts and special agents also were employed to collect data on valuation, taxation, and indebtedness; religion and libraries; colleges, academies, and schools; newspapers and periodicals, and wages.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1880 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series, which contains microdata.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau; after which the original sheets were transferred to various state archives, libraries, or universities.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is available in rolls from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along which digital indices.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1880 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census determined the resident population of the United States to be 50,189,209, an increase of 30.2 percent over the 38,555,983 persons enumerated during the 1870 census.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The mean center of United States population for 1880 was in Boone County, Kentucky.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The results from the census were used to determine the apportionment for the 48th, 49th, 50th, 51st, and 52nd sessions of the United States Congress.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The processing of the 1880 census data took so long (eight years) that the Census Bureau contracted Herman Hollerith to design and build a tabulating machine to be used for the next census.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census also led to the discovery of the Alabama paradox.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The **1890 United States census** was taken beginning June 2, 1890.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The census determined the resident population of the United States to be 62,979,766, an increase of 25.5 percent over the 50,189,209 persons enumerated during the 1880 census.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The data reported that the distribution of the population had resulted in the disappearance of the American frontier.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a majority of states recorded populations of over one million and the first in which three cities, New York City, Chicago, and Philadelphia, recorded populations of over one million.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The census also saw Chicago rise in rank to the nation's second-most populous city, a position it would hold until Los Angeles, the 57th-most populous city as of 1890, supplanted it in 1990.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] This was the first U.S. census to use machines to tabulate the collected data.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] Most of the 1890 census materials were destroyed on January 10, 1921, when the Commerce Department building caught fire, and in the subsequent disposal of the remaining damaged records.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The 1890 census was the first to be compiled using methods invented by Herman Hollerith and was overseen by Superintendents Robert P.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] Data was entered on a machine readable medium (punched cards) and tabulated by machine.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] Changes from the 1880 census included the larger population, the number of data items to be collected from individuals, the Census Bureau headcount, the volume of scheduled publications, and the use of Hollerith's electromechanical tabulators.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The net effect of these changes was to reduce the time required to process the census from eight years for the 1880 census to six years for the 1890 census.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The total population of 62,947,714, the family, or *rough*, count, was announced after only six weeks of processing (punched cards were not used for this tabulation).
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The public reaction to this tabulation was disbelief, as it was widely believed that the "right answer" was at least 75,000,000.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The United States census of 1890 showed a total of 248,253 Native Americans living in the United States, down from 400,764 Native Americans identified in the census of 1850.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The 1890 census announced that the frontier region of the United States no longer existed, and that the Census Bureau would no longer track the westward migration of the U.S. population.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] In practice, however, said migration can still be tracked by plotting each succeeding census' mean center of United States population.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] By 1890, settlement in the American West had reached sufficient population density that the frontier line had disappeared.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The original data for the 1890 census is mostly unavailable.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The population schedules were damaged in a fire in the basement of the U.S.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] Department of Commerce building in Washington, D.C. in 1921.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] Some 25% of the materials were presumed destroyed and another 50% damaged by smoke and water, although the actual damage may have been closer to 15–25%.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The damage to the records led to an outcry for a permanent National Archives.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] In December 1932, following standard federal record-keeping procedures, the Chief Clerk of the Bureau of the Census sent the Librarian of Congress a list of papers to be destroyed, including the original 1890 census schedules.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The Librarian was asked by the Bureau to identify any records which should be retained for historical purposes, but the Librarian did not accept the census records.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] Congress authorized destruction of that list of records on February 21, 1933, and the surviving original 1890 census records were destroyed by government order by 1934 or 1935.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] Few sets of microdata from the 1890 census survive.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] The **1900 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office on June 1, 1900, determined the resident population of the United States to be 76,212,168, an increase of 21.01% from the 62,979,766 persons enumerated during the 1890 census.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] It was the last census to be conducted before the founding of the permanent United States Census Bureau.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] The census saw the nation's largest city, New York City, more than double in size due to the consolidation with Brooklyn, becoming in the process the first U.S. city to record a population growth of over three million — Brooklyn was previously the 4th largest city in the United States on its own.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] Oversight of the statistics was by Frederick Howard Wines and Walter F.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1900 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] Statistician Frederick Ludwig Hoffman criticized the conduct of the census.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau in the 1940s, after which the original sheets were destroyed.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, and digital indices.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1900 census are freely available through IPUMS.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with electronic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] Location of 50 largest cities by population in the United States in 1900, on a map of the modern United States.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] The **1910 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau on April 15, 1910, determined the resident population of the United States to be 92,228,496, an increase of 21 percent over the 76,212,168 persons enumerated during the 1900 census.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] The 1910 census switched from a portrait page orientation to a landscape orientation.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] This was the last census in which Texas did not record any top 50 largest cities by population, despite being the 5th most populous state at the time.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] It was also the first census in which all the top 50 largest cities had population over 100,000.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] The 1910 census was the first to use metropolitan districts, the predecessor to modern metropolitan statistical areas, which were defined for all cities with at least 200,000 people.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Edward Dana Durand, then-head of the Bureau of Corporations, was appointed in 1909 to oversee the census. $14 million were allocated to conduct the census.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1910 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Number of dwelling house in order of visitation.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Number of family in order of visitation.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] NAME of each person whose place of abode on April 15, 1910, was in this family.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Enter surname first, then the given name and middle initial, if any.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Include every person living on April 15, 1910.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Omit children born since April 15, 1910.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Relationship of this person to the head of the family.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Whether single, married, widowed, or divorced.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Mother of how many children: Number born.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Mother of how many children: Number now living.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Place of birth of each person and parents of each person enumerated.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] If born in the United States, give the state or territory.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Place of birth of Father of this person.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Place of birth of Mother of this person.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Year of immigration to the United States.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Whether able to speak English; or, if not, give language spoken.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] General nature of industry, business, or establishment in which this person works, as *cotton mill, dry goods store, farm*, etc.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Whether as employer, employee, or work on own account.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Number of weeks out of work during year 1909.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Attended school any time since September 1, 1909.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Whether a survivor of the Union or Confederate Army or Navy.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Location of 50 largest cities by population in the United States in 1910.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau in the 1940s; after which the original sheets were destroyed.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along with digital indices.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1910-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1910 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] The **1920 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau during one month from January 5, 1920, determined the resident population of the United States to be 106,021,537, an increase of 15.0 percent over the 92,228,496 persons enumerated during the 1910 census.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] The 1920 Census was determined for 1 January 1920.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] The actual date of the enumeration appears on the heading of each page of the census schedule, but all responses were to reflect the individual's status as of 1 January, even if the status had changed between 1 January and the day of enumeration.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] In 1929, Congress passed the Reapportionment Act of 1929 which provided for a permanent method of reapportionment and fixed the number of representatives at 435.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the United States recorded a population of more than 100 million.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] It was also the first census in which a state—New York—recorded a population of more than ten million.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] This census also marked a significant population shift from rural to urban.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] According to the Census Bureau, "Beginning in 1910, the minimum population threshold to be categorized as an urban place was set at 2,500.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] 'Urban' was defined as including all territory, persons, and housing units within an incorporated area that met the population threshold.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1920 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] Location of 50 largest cities by population in the United States in 1920.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1920 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville was established by French Huguenots in 1764, at a site named by John de la Howe.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Famed states' rights advocate and Vice President John C.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Calhoun first practiced law in Abbeville, and he was born on a farm on the outskirts in what is now Mt.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville has the unique distinction of being both the birthplace and the deathbed of the Confederacy.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] On November 22, 1860, a meeting was held at Abbeville, at a site since dubbed "Secession Hill", to launch South Carolina's secession from the Union; one month later, the state of South Carolina became the first state to secede.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] At the end of the Civil War, with the Confederacy in shambles, Confederate President Jefferson Davis fled Richmond, Virginia, and headed south, stopping for a night in Abbeville at the home of his friend Armistead Burt.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] It was on May 2, 1865, in the front parlor of what is now known as the Burt-Stark Mansion that Jefferson Davis officially acknowledged the dissolution of the Confederate government, in the last official cabinet meeting.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] On December 8, 2003, in a 14-hour standoff that stemmed from a land-survey dispute, two Abbeville lawmen were killed by West Abbeville resident Steven Bixby.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] This siege has been compared by both sympathizers of the Bixbys and law enforcement agents to the events of Waco and Ruby Ridge.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] In February 2007, Steven Bixby was convicted on 17 counts including the two murders, as well as lesser charges of kidnapping and conspiracy.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] He was given two death sentences for the murders plus 125 years in prison on the other charges.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville is also the location of the tallest building in South Carolina, the Prysmian Copper Wire Tower.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Built in 2009, the tower is 373 feet (114 m) tall and has 30 floors.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville is located within the Piedmont Upland geographical region.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 6.1 square miles (15.9 km2), of which 0.012 square miles (0.03 km2), or 0.19%, is water.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen *Cfa*).
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Winters are cool, sometimes cold, and short in duration.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] The transitional seasons of spring and fall can vary in temperature but tend to be warm.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] In the summer highs usually peak in the mid 90s, but temperatures over 100 °F (37.8 °C) occur on occasion, most recently in the summer of 2012 during a heat wave.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] That year, the all-time record high of 109 °F (42.8 °C) was recorded on July 1.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] In the winter highs are in the low- to mid-50s and lows are right around freezing, seldom dropping below 25 °F (−3.9 °C).
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Precipitation is well distributed throughout the year.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Afternoon thunderstorms are a common occurrence in the summer months and can bring heavy winds and lightning.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] On March 31, 1973, an F4 tornado struck Abbeville and killed 7 people, making it the deadliest single tornado in 1973.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] The area was struck by two tornadoes on April 10, 2009.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] No fatalities were recorded, but the majority of the city lost power and many buildings sustained significant damage.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville first appeared in the 1850 U.S.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Census, when the town recorded a population of 1,252.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] As of the 2020 census, Abbeville had a population of 4,874.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] 23.0% of residents were under the age of 18 and 23.0% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] For every 100 females there were 78.4 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 74.5 males age 18 and over.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] 95.2% of residents lived in urban areas, while 4.8% lived in rural areas.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] There were 2,107 households in Abbeville, of which 30.8% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Of all households, 30.8% were married-couple households, 21.0% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 42.4% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] About 35.4% of all households were made up of individuals and 15.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] There were 2,436 housing units, of which 13.5% were vacant.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] The homeowner vacancy rate was 2.3% and the rental vacancy rate was 6.5%.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] As of the 2010 census the population of Abbeville was 5,237.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] The racial composition of the city was 46.9% White, 50.5% Black or African American, 0.9% Hispanic or Latino (of any race), 0.4% Asian, 0.2% Native American, 0.4% of other races, and 1.5% of Two or more races.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] As of the census of 2000, there were 5,840 people, 2,396 households, and 1,574 families residing in the city.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] The population density was 995.2 inhabitants per square mile (384.2/km2).
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] There were 2,654 housing units at an average density of 452.3 per square mile (174.6/km2).
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] The racial makeup of the city was 50.46% White, 48.48% African American, 0.12% Native American, 0.26% Asian, 0.02% Pacific Islander, 0.19% from other races, and 0.48% from two or more races.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 0.75% of the population.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] There were 2,396 households, out of which 30.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 37.1% were married couples living together, 23.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.3% were non-families.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] 30.6% of all households were made up of individuals, and 13.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] The average household size was 2.39 and the average family size was 2.97.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] In the city, the population was spread out, with 27.2% under the age of 18, 8.8% from 18 to 24, 25.9% from 25 to 44, 21.2% from 45 to 64, and 16.8% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] For every 100 females, there were 80.4 males.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 73.9 males.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] The median income for a household in the city was $25,756, and the median income for a family was $30,040.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Males had a median income of $28,339 versus $21,824 for females.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] The per capita income for the city was $13,274.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] About 16.3% of families and 19.8% of the population were below the poverty line, including 29.2% of those under age 18 and 20.9% of those age 65 or over.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville is the center of a small urban cluster with a total population of 6,038 (2000 census).
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Agriculture and forestry are important industries in the area.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Crops that are grown in quantities are cotton, corn, wheat, and hay.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Livestock, dairy cows, and poultry are also raised in the area.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Finally, textiles are the chief manufactured product, in particular, clothing.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] After the North American Free Trade Agreement clothing is no longer made in Abbeville.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Also represented are plastic and metal products.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville is in the Abbeville County School District.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville has Long Cane Primary, Westwood Elementary, J.S.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Wright Middle, Dixie High, and Abbeville High for schools.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville has a public library, a branch of the Abbeville County Library System.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] It also has some colleges, such as Piedmont Tech, Lander, Erskine, and many more.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville is the homeplace of a holiday pudding dessert called Gypsy.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Gypsy consists of pound or sponge cake, boiled custard, sherry, whipping cream, and almonds.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] Variations of recipe substituting bourbon for sherry exist.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] It resembles English trifle and has been referred to as "tipsy pudding" and southern tiramisu.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] It is usually cooked for Thanksgiving and/or Christmas in many "old Abbeville" families.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] The dish is not known to exist outside of Abbeville other than in families who moved from Abbeville elsewhere.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] It is usually served in a special stemmed, medium-sized, decorative crystal compote.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] The origins of Gypsy go back to late 19th century.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] There is a mention of *Gispy cake* in 1831 edition William Kitchiner's *The Cook's Oracle,* which may have been a prototype for the Abbeville Gypsy.
[src:abbeville-south-carolina/abbeville-south-carolina] A local legend tells a story of an unknown woman serving Gypsy to Confederate President Jefferson Davis at the end of the Civil War in 1865.
